         <abstract>
            <p>Based on the assumptions that (1) Federal defense expenditures will increase by $7 billion in this calendar year (in accord with the budget adjustments recommended by President Johnson on March 31), (2) Congress will enact the 10 percent tax surcharge, or its revenue equivalent, and will cut Federal spending modestly, and (3) the rate of personal saving will decline moderately, Dr. O'Leary forecasts that GNP will expand to about $853 billion in 1968, compared with $785 billion last year. The pattern is for a very strong first half with the rate of increase less vigorous in the second half. His analysis of the aggregate uses and sources of money and capital funds in 1968 concludes that interest rates will be firm throughout most of the year.</p>
          </abstract>
